THE shortage of jobs in Moletjie Village outside Polokwane in Limpopo will be eased soon.Chief Kgabo Moloto III of Bahlaloga Royal House held a sod turning ceremony in Ga-Rankua Village, where a farming market will be built. The agri-park programme has changed the lives of many people in the areas where it operates.Local youths will be trained by experienced farmers. The agri-park project is made up of two structures, a farmers&rsquo; production support unit and an agri-hub.Patrick Tshia, chairman of the agri-park in the Capricorn district, said: &ldquo;This project will benefit the people of Moletjie because farming will be restored. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the right time to develop rural areas. The project will create jobs for many people. &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll use the land that belongs to us. &ldquo;The vegetables from the farm will be sold at the hub.&rdquo; The chief said: &ldquo;Let&rsquo;s not undermine this project. &ldquo;We&rsquo;re lucky it has finally been successfully launched. &ldquo;This is not a small thing because it will benefit us all in the long run so let&rsquo;s support it because it&rsquo;s on our land.&rdquo; Sammy Selamolela, the district&rsquo;s acting mayor, said: &ldquo;This is a very good project because it&rsquo;s going to create job opportunities for the people of Moletjie. &ldquo;We applaud our chief for giving us the land, so let&rsquo;s stand up and work. &ldquo;The opportunity is good for our youth. &ldquo;The training will be helpful because it will develop and train people.&rdquo;